Train, Validation and Test split ¶

Before splitting into train and test, we will separate the between the target variable and all the rest of the variables, becoming X and Y respectively.

In [4]:
X = df.drop('isFraud', axis = 1)
Y = df.isFraud

Now we separate both into train + validation (x and y) and test (xtest, ytest)

In [5]:
x, xtest, y, ytest = train_test_split(X, Y, stratify= Y, 
                                      test_size=0.25, random_state=seed)

Performance Metric Selection ¶

Also we see that the proportion is practically the same. We conclude that the separtion is correct. Before starting with the models, we need to stablish which performance metric will be significant.

We understand that false negatives are more costly than false positives. False negatives can end up in a bad reputation and bad banking praxis (even more in a economic fine or even the institution closure). Meanwhile, false positives can meant in the usage of more resources in order to investigate the fraud. Hence, as can be devised in the image, we will be comparing our models based on the F2 score. Now we start with our models.

Base Model (Dummy) ¶

First model we will create is a dummy model which will predict that every transactions is not fraud. Due to the unbalance dataset, this will have a huge accuracy, the problem is that we will every possible false negative.

In [11]:
from sklearn.dummy import DummyClassifier
dummy = DummyClassifier(strategy="most_frequent")
dummy = dummy.fit(xtrain, ytrain)
y_pred_dummy = dummy.predict(xval)
yhat= dummy.predict_proba(xval)
